</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="329" pageNumber="330" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="329" pageNumber="330">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1821" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Blemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="329" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Blemus</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1821: 16. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1792" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Carabus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="329" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">Carabus discus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fabricius, 1792 designated by Westwood (1838: 5). Etymology. Uncertain, possibly from the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">blema</emphasis>
(a throw, cast; a shot, wound; a coverlet) [masculine]. The name was proposed by Franz Anton Ziegler and made available by Dejean.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="329" pageNumber="330">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Lasiotrechus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="329" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lasiotrechus</taxonomicName>
Ganglbauer, 1891a: 187, 191. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1792" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Carabus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="329" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">Carabus discus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fabricius, 1792 by monotypy. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">lasios</emphasis>
(hairy) and the generic name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clairville" authorityYear="1806" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Trechus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="329" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">Trechus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">q.v</emphasis>
.], alluding to the densely pubescent elytra (&quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="329" pageNumber="330">
Nur die 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Flügeldecken">Fluegeldecken</normalizedToken>
pubescent
</emphasis>
&quot;) of the adult [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="329" pageNumber="330" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="329" pageNumber="330">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="329" pageNumber="330">Two Palaearctic species, one of them adventive in North America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="329" pageNumber="330" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="329" pageNumber="330">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="329" pageNumber="330">
